My years were five and forty when I took up my pen and white hairs were seen among the black. Then all the world was under arms and Bohemond had assembled men from all the West, from the shores of the distant sea to the straits of Sicily and all the islands of the Ocean, English, Gauls, Saxons, Franks and Normans, men from Genoa and Pisa, Tuscans and Umbrians. Titese diverse peoples‚ each armed its native way, cameto the port of Bari, as many as are the birds of the air or the sands of the sea, differing in manners and in speech. They build them ships. Apulia and Calabria and Sicily send them flocks and herds and grain. They crass the sea, and soon the trumpets call to war and forth they go, destroy fields and towns and lay siege to Dyrrachium (Durazzo). The Emperor hears of their victorious advance and in his fear calls to his aid the far-flung peoples subject to his rule. Thebes sends its war-like hordes and the and that takes its name from Rome (Roumania); the Parthians come and Turks‚ Christ’s enemies, and Greeks from the Muses’ Mount and those who dwell along the Meander.
